<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Title (e</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Action on Hearing Loss [FBB0037]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">About us</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Action on Hearing Loss is the new name for RNID. We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">'</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">re the charity working for a world where hearing loss doesn't limit or label people, where tinnitus is silenced – and where people value and look after their hearing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Our response will focus on key issues that relate to people with hearing loss. Througho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">ut this response we use the term 'people with hearing loss' to refer to people with all levels of hearing loss, including people who are profoundly deaf.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We are happy for the details of this response to be made public. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Comments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Action on Hearing Loss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> wel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">comes the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">provide written evidence to the Culture, Media and Sport Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> concerning the future of the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> believe the BBC should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">pioneer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">broadcast</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> in terms of accessibility. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">The BBC to date ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> played an extremely important role within the broadcasting industry in promoting accessibility. The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">the most accessible broadcaster for people with hearing loss (although there ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">e still improvements they can make)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">e believe the BBC has been fundamental in encouraging other broadcasters to also improve their accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> through demonstrating the possibilities. The BBC has also helped to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">raise expectations amongst deaf people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">about what level of service </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">they can and should expect from all broadcasters. We therefore believe that ensuring everyone has access to BBC services has and should continue to be a key role for the BBC. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">This is particularly important with the development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> of catch up television and video on demand services, which are not currently regulated in terms of access services. </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">s mission and public purposes?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Accessibility is not currently explicit within the Public Purposes. However, the Agreement between the BBC and the Secretary of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">State for Culture, Media and Sport does include the requirement to have regard to the need to make services accessible to people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> with a visual or hearing impairment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We welcome the BBCs commitment to provide 100% subtitles on the majority of its programmes. We would like to see the accessibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">solutions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">extend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> further, for example, with the provision of subtitles on online vid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">eo clips. </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We would welcome an explicit statement within the public purposes regarding accessibility. This would help to highlight the importance of ensuring BBC services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> are accessible to disabled people. </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">What scope, scale a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">nd remit should the BBC have?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Please see answer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> to questions two and three above. </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">The BBC should absolutely retain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">and build on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">its commitment to provide accessible services to ensure that people with hearing loss are able to enjoy TV programmes to the same extent as everyone else. </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">What balance should be struck in what the BBC produces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We urge the BBC to ensure that all programmes, whether produced in house or commissioned externally, are accessible to people with hearing loss. This includes ensuring that producti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">on staff are aware of the issues around background noise and know how to reduce this. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Background noise, such as music, sound effects and ambient noise, can make it difficult for people with hearing loss to follow dialogue during a programme.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">In our 2008 an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">nual survey 87% of respondents agreed that background noise affects their ability to hear speech on television.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">It is also important that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">programmes are delivered to the BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">on schedule, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">with enough time to produce subtitles in advance of broadcast. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">ve subtitles have much higher error rates and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">pre-recorded subtitles are always preferable except for truly live programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">achieved an adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">No comment. </span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 34.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We believe the BBC should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> play a key role in developing technology. The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> the only broadcaster who ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> ensured that subtitles are available on the BBC iplayer when watched through the majority of platforms. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Currently no other broadcaster provides this functionality, meaning t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">hat deaf people do not have the same access to catch up and video on demand services as other people. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">We believe this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">pioneering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">role </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">is important, demonstrating to other broadcasters that accessibility is technologically feasible. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">The BBC has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> played a pioneering role within the broadcast industry in terms of accessibility for deaf people. We would like to see this role continued and built upon, ensuring that all BBC services are accessible to people with hearing loss, thereby encouraging other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> broadcasters to do the same. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>